<font color="#FF0000">BEGINNING OF SURVIVOR'S GUILT</font><br>
<tt>Fri Jul 25  1:10:19 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
While on the subject of Surviving... how about Arriving!  I remember arriving in Viet Nam two times.  The first was different from the second.  I guess you can only be an FNG once.  On arrival, for my second tour, I was accompanied by hundreds of FNG's  I wanted to tell them something... but I didn't know what to say... so I didn't.  I looked at them when they were not looking at me.  I wondered how many of them would make it home alive... I wondered if I would survive it all a second time.  I stared out the window and wished whatever was going to happen... would hurry up and get over with.<br><br>
&quot;The New Guy&quot;<br><br>
My brass was carefully polished<br>
and my boots were mirrors of black.<br>
I proffered forth my silver wings,<br>
as I rolled my shoulders back.<br><br>
While dragging my duffel off the dusty ramp,<br>
I rehearsed my plan of attack,<br>
&quot;Strike terror in the hearts of the enemy<br>
and teach the others what they lack.&quot;<br><br>
It was Aret^e that braced the Trojan warrior,<br>
Us`i maya ye... for the Tetonwan Sioux.<br>
Me, I was filled with the vigor of youth<br>
and knew exactly what brave men do.<br><br>
&quot;Take up the cause for this motley nation,<br>
give them courage `neath the Red White and Blue.&quot;<br>
&quot;Simply be gallant, noble and valiant,<br>
and they all will take heed of you.&quot;<br><br>
&quot;That's Camp Alpha,&quot; the sergeant barked,<br>
pointing at a city of sandbags and tin.<br>
He herded us up with the skill of a drover<br>
and like sheep, he ushered us in.<br><br>
But, once inside those bowels of wire,<br>
my strong countenance started to dim.<br>
My freshness reeked; my arrogaance crumbled,<br>
in the company of hollow-eyed men.<br><br>
No feelings or thoughts nor friendship was offered.<br>
There was nothing for a new man to borrow.<br>
They closed me out behind sun-parched lips<br>
and weary eyes that were cool and narrow.<br><br>
In their green faded shirts and moldy boots,<br>
they looked down on me with sorrow.<br>
The thousand years they had finished yesterday,<br>
they knew I would begin tomorrow.<br><br>
Why I lived, I will never know,<br>
for I was certainly not the best.<br>
Yet, in the crimson tide, where so many died,<br>
I was borne above the crest.<br><br>
Later, back at Camp Alpha, the grandest of places<br>
I kicked back for a short-timer's rest.<br>
In filthy rags and rotten boots,<br>
with faded black wings on my chest.<br><br>
Deep within, I licked my wounds,<br>
moving only to swat the flies.<br>
I jumped, when he spoke and glared at him,<br>
as he backed away in surprise...<br>
...A tender youth in glistening boots,<br>
......with silver wings on his chest...<br>
........and a questioning look in his eyes.<br><br>
From &quot;Scars and Stripes, Forever&quot; copyrite 1990 by Edward Ramon
